Hello Josef! üòä First, it‚Äôs important to highlight that the `\core\event\config_log_created` event is indeed triggered when an administrative setting is changed, but it doesn‚Äôt directly carry the user who made the change, as you correctly pointed out. Here‚Äôs a simple and efficient tip to solve this: you can capture the user information directly from the global session variable `$USER` when the event is triggered. The `$USER` variable contains all the details of the currently logged-in user. This eliminates the need to query the database or correlate IDs, making your code faster and more reliable. Here‚Äôs how you can implement it: 
```text
global $USER;




// Get the logged-in user's ID 


 $id = $USER->id; 




 // Get the logged-in user's full name 


 $fullname = fullname($USER); 





// Use these details to compose your notification 


$notification = "User {$fullname}, ID: {$id}, changed an administrative setting.";
```
 With this method, you will be capturing the information directly from the active session at the moment the event is triggered. This approach works well because the event is fired in the same context as the setting change, where `$USER` is still accessible. Eduardo Kraus Teacher and programmer üíª

Assuming $record is the result of looping over the SQL query 
```text
foreach ($records as $record) {}
```
 $record would only contain the data from the database table, not any methods (thus the undefined method error). If you want to generate the date in SQL, you can use an alias to return a nicer fieldname you can iterate over. e.g. 
```text
SELECT (DATE(FROM_UNIXTIME(search_time)) searchtime FROM {searchlogtable};
```
 then you can iterate over the results using $result->searchtime If you want to do the conversion in PHP, you can either use the PHP native date('Y-m-d H:m:s', $timestamp) or you could use Moodle's userdate($timestamp) function that will use the standard date/time format used in Moodle. In your code above, it would look something like: 
```text
foreach ($results as $result) {
    $result->search_time = userdate($result->search_time);
}
```

